, and Croatian <b>Ambrož</b> (see   Ambroz  ), and also their derivatives, e.g. the Slovenian patronymic <b>Ambrožič</b>.","Irish: from <b>Mac Ambróis</b> ‘son of Ambrose’ (see 1 above); a West Munster name, which has also been Anglicized as   McCambridge  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":12,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":25,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":34,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor de Braose was born about 1303, in Stradbroke, Suffolk, England, her father, Richard de Braose, was 25 and her mother, Alianor Shelton, was 23. She had at least 1 daughter with Gilbert de Glanville. She died in 1376, in England, at the age of 74."},"et":{"Abt 1303–1376":"umbes 1303–1376","1303–1376":"1303–1376","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","–1375":"–1375","1280–1361":"1280–1361","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","Abt 1303":"umbes 1303","1361":"1361","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1376":"1376","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","27 August 1375":"27. august 1375","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wingfield, Suffolk, England":"Wingfield, Suffolk, England","Stradbroke, Suffolk, , England":"Stradbroke, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Stradbroke, Suffolk, England":"Stradbroke, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1303–1376":"noin 1303–1376","1303–1376":"1303–1376","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","–1375":"–1375","1280–1361":"1280–1361","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","Abt 1303":"noin 1303","1361":"1361","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1376":"1376","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","27 August 1375":"27. elokuuta 1375","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wingfield, Suffolk, England":"Wingfield, Suffolk, Engl